//! CLI command implementations.
//!
//! Each submodule owns one or more related `Commands` variants:
//!
//! | Module          | Commands handled                                   |
//! |-----------------|-----------------------------------------------------|
//! | `run`           | `Run`, `Phase`                                     |
//! | `phase`         | `List`, `Status`, `Reset`, `Audit`                 |
//! | `project`       | `Init`, `Interview`, `Generate`, `Implement`       |
//! | `patterns`      | `Learn`, `Patterns`                                |
//! | `config`        | `Config`                                           |
//! | `skills`        | `Skills`                                           |
//! | `compact`       | `Compact`                                          |
//! | `swarm`         | `Swarm`                                            |
//! | `factory`       | `Factory`                                          |

pub mod compact;
pub mod config;
pub mod factory;
pub mod patterns;
pub mod phase;
pub mod project;
pub mod run;
pub mod skills;
pub mod swarm;

pub use compact::cmd_compact;
pub use config::cmd_config;
pub use factory::cmd_factory;
pub use patterns::{cmd_learn, cmd_patterns};
pub use phase::{cmd_audit, cmd_list, cmd_reset, cmd_status};
pub use project::{cmd_generate, cmd_implement, cmd_init, cmd_interview};
pub use run::{run_orchestrator, run_single_phase};
pub use skills::cmd_skills;
pub use swarm::{cmd_swarm, cmd_swarm_abort, cmd_swarm_status};

content.text:
### Run Codex CLI in Interactive and Non-Interactive Modes

Source: https://context7.com/openai/codex/llms.txt

Examples demonstrating how to start Codex CLI in an interactive REPL, execute tasks with an initial prompt, enable full-auto mode, request JSON output, specify a different AI model, and configure sandbox policies for command execution.

```bash
# Start interactive REPL
codex

# Run with initial prompt
codex "explain this codebase to me"

# Run in full-auto mode (network disabled, sandboxed)
codex --approval-mode full-auto "create a todo-list app"

# Non-interactive quiet mode with JSON output
codex -q --json "explain utils.ts"

# Specify a different model
codex --model gpt-4.1 "refactor this function"

# Run with specific sandbox policy
codex --sandbox workspace-write "update the README"
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Sandbox Policies for Command Execution Security

Source: https://context7.com/openai/codex/llms.txt

Define fine-grained sandbox policies for secure command execution including full access, read-only, workspace write, and external sandbox modes. Each policy type controls network access, file system permissions, and resource restrictions. Choose appropriate policy based on execution environment and security requirements.

```typescript
// Full access (dangerous - only in containers)
const dangerFullAccess = {
  type: 'dangerFullAccess'
};

// Read-only access
const readOnly = {
  type: 'readOnly',
  networkAccess: false,
  access: {
    type: 'restricted',
    readableRoots: ['/project', '/usr/local/lib'],
    includePlatformDefaults: true
  }
};

// Workspace write (recommended for development)
const workspaceWrite = {
  type: 'workspaceWrite',
  networkAccess: false,
  excludeSlashTmp: false,
  excludeTmpdirEnvVar: false,
  writableRoots: ['/project', '/home/user/.codex/memories'],
  readOnlyAccess: {
    type: 'fullAccess'
  }
};

// External sandbox (for container environments)
const externalSandbox = {
  type: 'externalSandbox',
  networkAccess: 'restricted'  // or 'enabled'
};
```

--------------------------------

### Read and Write Configuration Values Programmatically

Source: https://context7.com/openai/codex/llms.txt

Programmatically read and modify Codex configuration values including model selection, approval policies, and sandbox modes. Supports single value writes and batch operations with responses indicating configuration layer (default, user, project, session) and source file paths.

```typescript
// Read configuration values
const configReadParams = {
  jsonrpc: '2.0',
  id: 13,
  method: 'config/read',
  params: {
    keys: ['model', 'approval_policy', 'sandbox_mode']
  }
};

// Write single config value
const configWriteParams = {
  jsonrpc: '2.0',
  id: 14,
  method: 'config/write',
  params: {
    key: 'model',
    value: 'gpt-4.1'
  }
};

// Batch write multiple values
const configBatchWriteParams = {
  jsonrpc: '2.0',
  id: 15,
  method: 'config/batchWrite',
  params: {
    edits: [
      { key: 'model', value: 'o4-mini' },
      { key: 'model_reasoning_effort', value: 'high' },
      { key: 'sandbox_mode', value: 'workspace-write' }
    ]
  }
};

// Response shows applied values and layer info
interface ConfigReadResponse {
  values: {
    [key: string]: {
      value: any;
      layer: 'default' | 'user' | 'project' | 'session';
      source: string;  // file path if from config file
    };
  };
}
```

--------------------------------

### Configure Codex CLI via config.toml

Source: https://context7.com/openai/codex/llms.txt

An example `config.toml` file demonstrating how to customize various aspects of Codex CLI behavior, including model settings, approval policies, sandbox modes, history persistence, TUI preferences, custom model provider configurations, MCP server settings, and feature flags.

```toml
# ~/.codex/config.toml

# Model configuration
model = "o4-mini"
model_reasoning_effort = "medium"  # none, minimal, low, medium, high, xhigh
model_reasoning_summary = "concise"  # auto, concise, detailed, none

# Approval policy: untrusted, on-failure, on-request, never
approval_policy = "on-request"

# Sandbox mode: read-only, workspace-write, danger-full-access
sandbox_mode = "workspace-write"

# History settings
[history]
persistence = "save-all"  # save-all, none
max_bytes = 10485760  # 10MB limit

# TUI settings
[tui]
animations = true
notifications = true
theme = "dark"
alternate_screen = "auto"  # auto, always, never

# Custom model provider
[model_providers."custom-provider"]
name = "Custom Provider"
base_url = "https://api.custom-provider.com/v1"
env_key = "CUSTOM_API_KEY"
wire_api = "responses"

# MCP server configuration
[mcp_servers.filesystem]
command = "npx"
args = ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-filesystem", "/path/to/allowed/dir"]
enabled = true

[mcp_servers.github]
command = "npx"
args = ["-y", "@modelcontextprotocol/server-github"]
env = { GITHUB_TOKEN = "your-token" }

# Feature flags
[features]
memories = true
web_search = false
multi_agent = true
```

--------------------------------

### Execute standalone command in Codex sandbox

Source: https://github.com/openai/codex/blob/main/codex-rs/app-server/README.md

Sends a command/exec request to run a standalone command in the server's sandbox without creating a thread or turn. The request includes optional parameters for working directory, environment variables, PTY size, sandbox policy, output capture limits, and timeout configuration. Returns exit code and captured stdout/stderr streams.

```json
{ "method": "command/exec", "id": 32, "params": {
    "command": ["ls", "-la"],
    "processId": "ls-1",
    "cwd": "/Users/me/project",
    "env": { "FOO": "override" },
    "size": { "rows": 40, "cols": 120 },
    "sandboxPolicy": { "type": "workspaceWrite" },
    "outputBytesCap": 1048576,
    "disableOutputCap": false,
    "timeoutMs": 10000,
    "disableTimeout": false
} }
{ "id": 32, "result": {
    "exitCode": 0,
    "stdout": "...",
    "stderr": ""
} }
```

